servings: 2
---

Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @sweet potato{2} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel).

Pop the sweet potato onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and tender, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Drain and rinse the @black beans{1%tin} in a #sieve{}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the @British chicken breast{260%g}(diced) to the pan and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook until browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Add the garlic, @harissa paste{50%g} and @chermoula spice mix{1/2} (add less of both if you'd prefer things milder) to the chicken. Cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1%tin}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @water for the sauce{200%ml}. Bring to a boil, then reduce the heat. Simmer, stirring occasionally, until slightly reduced, ~{7-8%minutes}.

When the sauce has reduced, add the black beans and continue to simmer, stirring occasionally, until the stew has thickened, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once the sweet potato is cooked, remove from the oven and stir through the stew.

Stir in the @baby spinach{40%g} a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Add a splash of @?water{} if the stew is a little thick.

When ready, share your harissa stew between your #bowls{} and top with a dollop of @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g}.

Sprinkle over the @toasted flaked almonds{15%g} to finish.

Enjoy!